Are you. um.
lonely or something. Virgil?

253
00:16:27.589 --> 00:16:28.798
MASON: He went out happy.

254
00:16:28.881 --> 00:16:32.130
Well. if happy's drowning
in panties and a matching bra.

255
00:16:32.214 --> 00:16:33.255
yeah. why not?

256
00:16:34.547 --> 00:16:36.547
He was wearing man clothes
on the outside.

257
00:16:42.297 --> 00:16:43.714
What's with that?

258
00:16:43.798 --> 00:16:45.172
Oh. my next patient.

259
00:16:45.255 --> 00:16:47.756
Kidnapping gone way wrong.

260
00:16:47.839 --> 00:16:49.547
Worst thing you ever seen.

261
00:16:49.631 --> 00:16:51.214
What do you know what I've seen?

262
00:17:02.923 --> 00:17:04.506
How's this?

263
00:17:04.589 --> 00:17:06.589
I like it better than the suit.

264
00:17:10.923 --> 00:17:13.631
I got a domestic stabbing
with a three piece. if you want.

265
00:17:13.714 --> 00:17:16.089
FENTON BOSTWICK: Mr. Mason.
in what capacity were you hired

266
00:17:16.172 --> 00:17:17.673
- by the defense?
- I was hired

267
00:17:17.756 --> 00:17:18.923
as a private investigator.

268
00:17:19.005 --> 00:17:21.839
And is that.
these private investigations.

269
00:17:21.923 --> 00:17:24.589
the current means
by which you earn a living?

270
00:17:24.673 --> 00:17:27.172
- You know it is. Fenton.
- (JUDGE CLEARS THROAT)

271
00:17:27.255 --> 00:17:30.798
Um. pardon me.
Uh. yes. Mr. Bostwick.

272
00:17:30.881 --> 00:17:32.881
BOSTWICK: Now.
am I correct in asserting

273
00:17:32.964 --> 00:17:35.255
that you were recently cited
for assault?

274
00:17:39.005 --> 00:17:41.214
- Mr. Mason.
- I'm sorry. What?

275
00:17:41.297 --> 00:17:42.881
A complaint for assault.

276
00:17:42.964 --> 00:17:45.065
- This is irrelevant. Your Honor.
- BOSTWICK: I'm sure

277
00:17:45.089 --> 00:17:46.774
- that you resent this line...
- No. what I resent

278
00:17:46.798 --> 00:17:48.589
is Alvin Rutherford
showing up repeatedly

279
00:17:48.673 --> 00:17:50.673
and offering me pennies
on the dollar for a home

280
00:17:50.756 --> 00:17:52.214
my father built
with his own hands.

281
00:17:52.297 --> 00:17:54.798
Tragic. Mr. Mason. but assault?

282
00:17:56.089 --> 00:17:57.547
I threw a cowpie at him.

283
00:17:57.631 --> 00:17:59.756
(LAUGHTER)

284
00:17:59.839 --> 00:18:01.214
BOSTWICK: That's funny.

285
00:18:01.297 --> 00:18:03.673
However. far less amusing

286
00:18:03.756 --> 00:18:07.089
is the dishonorable end
to your military career.

287
00:18:09.464 --> 00:18:11.089
That has nothing to do
with this trial.

288
00:18:11.172 --> 00:18:13.589
BOSTWICK: A blue discharge
for conduct unbecoming.

289
00:18:13.673 --> 00:18:15.923
Would you care to elaborate
on that. Mr. Mason?

290
00:18:16.005 --> 00:18:19.130
- Was that a mistake?
- Feel free to jump in. Frank.

291
00:18:19.506 --> 00:18:21.547
Objection.

292
00:18:21.631 --> 00:18:23.881
- Question of relevance.
- You're goddamn right.

293
00:18:23.964 --> 00:18:25.089
JUDGE: Sustained.

294
00:18:25.172 --> 00:18:26.881
- Watch the God talk. sir.
- Sorry.

295
00:18:26.964 --> 00:18:28.148
BOSTWICK:
Nothing further. Your Honor.

296
00:18:28.172 --> 00:18:29.815
MASON: E.B. send you
'cause he thought I forgot

297
00:18:29.839 --> 00:18:30.923
the way to the office?

298
00:18:31.005 --> 00:18:32.190
DELLA STREET:
The meeting's changed.

299
00:18:32.214 --> 00:18:33.798
We're going to Pasadena now.

300
00:18:33.881 --> 00:18:35.422
We are?
Fine. we can take my truck.

301
00:18:35.506 --> 00:18:38.506
We could if the plan was to make
the world's worst impression.

302
00:18:38.589 --> 00:18:39.909
Oh. I don't have to
plan for that.

303
00:18:39.964 --> 00:18:41.214
That happens naturally.

304
00:18:41.297 --> 00:18:43.190
I'll say. you were just four
words from contempt of court.

305
00:18:43.214 --> 00:18:45.255
Go fuck yourself.
I could have got that in.

306
00:18:45.339 --> 00:18:47.589
Thus demonstrating
your masterful knowledge

307
00:18:47.673 --> 00:18:49.714
- of legal decorum.
- Frank Dillon is sitting there

308
00:18:49.798 --> 00:18:52.089
like a monument to the useless
and the judge is concerned

309
00:18:52.172 --> 00:18:54.297
with my decorum?
Why didn't he hold him

310
00:18:54.381 --> 00:18:56.422
in contempt?
Because I sure as hell did.

311
00:18:56.506 --> 00:18:57.964
Letting him dig into me
like that.

312
00:18:58.047 --> 00:19:00.089
A fucking peanut vendor
would have known to object.

313
00:19:00.172 --> 00:19:02.422
So many windmills.
so little time.

314
00:19:06.297 --> 00:19:07.756
How are you today. Miss Street?

315
00:19:09.089 --> 00:19:10.130
Peachy.

316
00:19:10.214 --> 00:19:12.047
How are you. Mr. Mason?

317
00:19:13.589 --> 00:19:15.964
HERMAN BAGGERLY: I wasn't
expecting a congregation.

318
00:19:16.047 --> 00:19:18.005
E.B.: I rely on Miss Street

319
00:19:18.089 --> 00:19:19.756
to keep the facts straight.
Herman.

320
00:19:19.839 --> 00:19:21.714
Do you intend
to take notes. Miss?

321
00:19:21.798 --> 00:19:23.631
DELLA:
That's generally what I do.

322
00:19:23.714 --> 00:19:25.422
Unless you object.

323
00:19:26.297 --> 00:19:28.464
And you're a detective.
Mr. Mason?

324
00:19:28.547 --> 00:19:31.089
It's a fancy word
for a busybody. but yes.

325
00:19:31.172 --> 00:19:35.172
We've been working together
since. uh... when was it?

326
00:19:35.255 --> 00:19:36.756
Just after the war.

327
00:19:36.839 --> 00:19:39.172
Gave him his first job back
from France.

328
00:19:39.255 --> 00:19:41.798
- isn't that right. Perry?
- HERMAN: You served overseas?

329
00:19:41.881 --> 00:19:43.214
With lots of other farm boys.

330
00:19:43.297 --> 00:19:45.005
Mr. Mason was in the army.

331
00:19:45.089 --> 00:19:48.172
survived
the Battle of the Argonne.

332
00:19:48.255 --> 00:19:50.839
How can we help you.
Mr. Baggerly?

333
00:19:50.923 --> 00:19:53.756
HERMAN: It's not me
that needs help. Mr. Mason.

334
00:19:53.839 --> 00:19:57.005
Matthew and Emily Dodson.

335
00:19:57.089 --> 00:19:59.547
an unspeakable act

336
00:19:59.631 --> 00:20:02.005
was visited upon them.
they're quite overwhelmed.

337
00:20:02.089 --> 00:20:04.255
E.B.: Consider us
at their service.

338
00:20:05.631 --> 00:20:09.631
- Friends of yours?
- Members of my church.

339
00:20:09.714 --> 00:20:12.130
Working people
without many resources.

340
00:20:12.214 --> 00:20:15.589
E.B.: Well. God has put you
in their path.

341
00:20:16.297 --> 00:20:18.005
Is this a...

342
00:20:18.089 --> 00:20:19.714
HERMAN: Radiant Assembly of God.

343
00:20:19.798 --> 00:20:23.047
- Right. On the radio.
- Sister Alice.

344
00:20:23.130 --> 00:20:25.756
A woman of wonder-working power.

345
00:20:25.839 --> 00:20:29.047
I won't hesitate to say
that she changed my life.

346
00:20:29.130 --> 00:20:33.339
Do the Dodsons know
you contacted me. Herman?

347
00:20:33.422 --> 00:20:36.673
They're anxiously
awaiting your guidance. Elias.

348
00:20:36.756 --> 00:20:38.005
What about the police?

349
00:20:39.631 --> 00:20:40.714
How's that?

350
00:20:40.798 --> 00:20:42.714
Well. they'll be
on this hammer and tongs.

351
00:20:42.798 --> 00:20:44.089
Why not leave it to them?

352
00:20:48.839 --> 00:20:50.422
I'll be frank. Mr. Mason.

353
00:20:52.464 --> 00:20:55.214
I don't trust the Los Angeles
Police Department

354
00:20:55.297 --> 00:20:56.798
to do the job that's needed.

355
00:20:59.673 --> 00:21:01.005
Neither would I.

356
00:21:04.964 --> 00:21:07.673
(OVERLAPPING CHATTER)

357
00:21:12.631 --> 00:21:14.190
STEVE HOLCOMB:
So you found this upstairs?

358
00:21:14.214 --> 00:21:15.881
MATTHEW:
I told you. my wife did.

359
00:21:15.964 --> 00:21:17.839
- I was at work.
- And she called you?

360
00:21:18.631 --> 00:21:20.547
Yeah. Hysterical.

361
00:21:20.631 --> 00:21:22.506
Why neither one of you
call the police?

362
00:21:23.172 --> 00:21:24.297
Read the note.

363
00:21:25.005 --> 00:21:27.589
You can read. can't you?

364
00:21:27.673 --> 00:21:31.422
So your wife finds the note.
calls you. what she do next?

365
00:21:31.506 --> 00:21:32.906
MATTHEW:
How should I know? Ask her.

366
00:21:32.964 --> 00:21:34.523
DETECTIVE ENNIS:
We'll get to her in a minute.

367
00:21:34.547 --> 00:21:36.381
HOLCOMB:
You own a grocery store.

368
00:21:36.464 --> 00:21:38.881
- much money in that?
- What?

369
00:21:39.005 --> 00:21:40.422
HOLCOMB:
Nice house for a grocer.

370
00:21:40.506 --> 00:21:42.297
It can't be cheap to maintain.

371
00:21:42.381 --> 00:21:43.649
MATTHEW:
What's that supposed to mean?

372
00:21:43.673 --> 00:21:45.255
HOLCOMB:
How long does it take to get

373
00:21:45.339 --> 00:21:47.106
- from the grocery store to here?
- MATTHEW:
What difference does it make?

374
00:21:47.130 --> 00:21:48.440
- Easy. Matthew...
- How am... Are you suggesting

375
00:21:48.464 --> 00:21:51.631
I had something to do with it?
What the hell?

376
00:21:51.714 --> 00:21:53.398
ENNIS: Just covering
all angles. Mr. Dodson.

377
00:21:53.422 --> 00:21:54.690
MATTHEW:
Where was I? Who saw me?

378
00:21:54.714 --> 00:21:55.964
I didn't kidnap my son.

379
00:21:56.047 --> 00:21:58.523
- I didn't murder my own son.
- E.B.: No one is saying you did.

380
00:21:58.547 --> 00:22:00.547
MATTHEW: Well. he is!
And he's dancing around.

381
00:22:00.631 --> 00:22:02.130
but that's what
he fucking thinks.

382
00:22:02.214 --> 00:22:04.214
E.B.: Maybe this is a good time
for a little break.

383
00:22:04.297 --> 00:22:06.547
Sound okay to you.
Detective Holcomb?

384
00:22:09.547 --> 00:22:10.923
Yeah. Why not.

385
00:22:11.005 --> 00:22:13.381
- E.B.: Get some fresh air.
- MATTHEW: It's all right.

386
00:22:13.464 --> 00:22:14.824
You treated me like...
You can't...

387
00:22:14.881 --> 00:22:16.523
- You can't just walk...
- E.B.: Easy now. Matthew.

388
00:22:16.547 --> 00:22:18.756
Let's have a little drink
of cold water. shall we?

389
00:22:19.756 --> 00:22:21.339
MATTHEW:
Water. Right. great idea.

390
00:22:21.422 --> 00:22:22.464
That'll fix everything.

391
00:22:22.547 --> 00:22:24.589
E.B.:
It's all part of the process.

392
00:22:25.547 --> 00:22:27.381
(COMMOTION OUTSIDE)

393
00:22:33.255 --> 00:22:36.255
(FLOOR CREAKING)

394
00:22:42.422 --> 00:22:46.756
♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

395
00:22:50.089 --> 00:22:51.589
(CAMERA CLICKS)

396
00:24:20.130 --> 00:24:22.714
EMILY: Are you the man
that works with Mr. Jonathan?

397
00:24:25.547 --> 00:24:28.673
Yes. ma'am. Perry.

398
00:24:32.881 --> 00:24:34.506
I'm Emily Dodson.

399
00:24:35.381 --> 00:24:36.547
Charlie's mother.

400
00:24:43.589 --> 00:24:45.589
Offer you a cigarette.
Mrs. Dodson?

401
00:24:47.881 --> 00:24:49.756
If you promise not to tell
my husband.

402
00:24:51.547 --> 00:24:52.756
Wouldn't dream of it.

403
00:25:11.214 --> 00:25:12.255
EMILY: Thank you.

404
00:25:16.547 --> 00:25:18.589
You were in the war.
weren't you?

405
00:25:20.923 --> 00:25:22.964
The way you hold your cigarette.

406
00:25:23.047 --> 00:25:24.631
Hiding the ember in your palm.

407
00:25:25.589 --> 00:25:27.190
I guess I'm still trained
not to give them

408
00:25:27.214 --> 00:25:28.381
something to shoot at.

409
00:25:30.005 --> 00:25:32.047
Was your husband over there?

410
00:25:34.005 --> 00:25:35.047
Brother.

411
00:25:36.172 --> 00:25:39.047
I haven't seen him
since we left Missouri.

412
00:25:39.130 --> 00:25:41.589
I really wish they'd let me
clean in here.

413
00:25:43.756 --> 00:25:45.297
All this fingerprint dust...

414
00:25:46.923 --> 00:25:50.839
Can't help feeling that it
reflects poorly on me somehow.

415
00:25:51.881 --> 00:25:54.339
Oh. I don't...
I don't think poorly of you.

416
00:25:56.798 --> 00:25:57.798
God does.

417
00:25:59.798 --> 00:26:01.172
That's why I'm being punished.

418
00:26:06.130 --> 00:26:08.714
Do you have children. Mr. Perry?

419
00:26:08.798 --> 00:26:11.839
It's... It's Mason.
Perry is my first name.

420
00:26:13.047 --> 00:26:14.172
I have a son.

421
00:26:16.005 --> 00:26:17.422
What's his name?

422
00:26:20.631 --> 00:26:21.798
Theodore.

423
00:26:21.881 --> 00:26:22.964
Teddy.

424
00:26:24.964 --> 00:26:26.381
How old?

425
00:26:26.464 --> 00:26:28.130
MASON: Nine in February.

426
00:26:32.172 --> 00:26:33.547
EMILY: Charlie likes turtles.

427
00:26:36.172 --> 00:26:37.297
Liked.

428
00:26:41.381 --> 00:26:42.964
What's your boy fond of?

429
00:26:47.130 --> 00:26:48.172
Firetrucks.

430
00:26:53.339 --> 00:26:54.673
(GRIMACING) I bet

431
00:26:56.255 --> 00:26:59.214
nine is a good age for a boy.

432
00:27:04.923 --> 00:27:07.839
(SOBBING)

433
00:27:11.547 --> 00:27:12.714
So.

434
00:27:15.381 --> 00:27:16.589
I'm sorry.

435
00:27:23.964 --> 00:27:26.464
(TYPEWRITER KEYS CLACKING)

436
00:27:26.547 --> 00:27:27.867
MASON: Yeah. fine.
he's a hothead.

437
00:27:27.923 --> 00:27:30.005
but he's a little too touchy
if you ask me.

438
00:27:30.756 --> 00:27:31.964
And her?

439
00:27:32.047 --> 00:27:34.756
She was just sitting
downstairs the whole time?

440
00:27:34.839 --> 00:27:37.464
E.B.: She told the detectives
she gave the boy a bath.

441
00:27:37.547 --> 00:27:40.464
put him to bed.
fell asleep by the fire

442
00:27:40.547 --> 00:27:41.964
listening to the radio.

443
00:27:42.047 --> 00:27:44.381
DELLA: Actually.
she puts Charlie to bed.

444
00:27:44.464 --> 00:27:46.422
goes downstairs
to clean up the kitchen.

445
00:27:46.506 --> 00:27:48.381
goes back upstairs
to check on him

446
00:27:48.464 --> 00:27:50.339
then goes downstairs
and falls asleep

447
00:27:50.422 --> 00:27:51.756
listening to the radio.

448
00:27:52.798 --> 00:27:54.756
She doesn't twitch an eyelid

449
00:27:54.839 --> 00:27:56.631
while someone creeps
into her house

450
00:27:56.714 --> 00:27:58.506
and nabs her kid?

451
00:27:58.589 --> 00:28:02.130
- You think she's a drinker?
- DELLA: No. She's a mother.

452
00:28:02.214 --> 00:28:05.005
Feeding. changing.
burping. screaming.

453
00:28:05.089 --> 00:28:06.422
you wouldn't last a minute.

454
00:28:06.506 --> 00:28:08.839
MASON: Is this something
you know about?

455
00:28:08.923 --> 00:28:10.923
DELLA:
Call it an educated guess.

456
00:28:15.589 --> 00:28:17.506
MASON: All right.
You're the kidnapper.

457
00:28:17.589 --> 00:28:19.673
you have to case that house
long enough to know.

458
00:28:19.756 --> 00:28:21.506
Matthew's hours
at the grocery store.

459
00:28:21.589 --> 00:28:23.798
the time Emily
gives Charlie the bath.

460
00:28:23.881 --> 00:28:26.506
then puts him down.
then falls asleep herself.

461
00:28:26.589 --> 00:28:28.297
unless you have someone
on the inside.

462
00:28:28.381 --> 00:28:30.422
Oh. so you agree
with the police.

463
00:28:30.506 --> 00:28:33.047
You think the Dodsons
had something to do with it.

464
00:28:33.130 --> 00:28:35.964
- I'm not agreeing with anyone.
- I sure hope not.

465
00:28:36.047 --> 00:28:37.339
I've stood with those two.

466
00:28:37.964 --> 00:28:40.214
That's grief. not guilt.

467
00:28:40.297 --> 00:28:42.214
MASON: I'm just pointing out
that someone knew

468
00:28:42.297 --> 00:28:44.089
they were good
for a hundred grand.

469
00:28:44.172 --> 00:28:45.631
How do you figure that
from a guy

470
00:28:45.714 --> 00:28:48.839
who sells pickled cucumbers
and aftershave?

471
00:28:48.923 --> 00:28:50.464
It's queer from both sides.

472
00:28:50.547 --> 00:28:51.923
DELLA: And the baby.

473
00:28:52.964 --> 00:28:56.589
Someone stood over Charlie
and stitched those eyes.

474
00:29:00.005 --> 00:29:01.673
Yeah. it's a dark tone.

475
00:29:01.756 --> 00:29:04.255
long. long. deep. dark tone.

476
00:29:07.589 --> 00:29:09.881
(SIGHS) Wipe it off. gentles.

477
00:29:09.964 --> 00:29:11.547
We do what we're asked to do.

478
00:29:11.631 --> 00:29:13.881
Well. that's easy for you
to say.

479
00:29:13.964 --> 00:29:16.148
Detectives aren't gonna like me
over their shoulder on this.

480
00:29:16.172 --> 00:29:17.690
And I got a license
that could get pulled.

481
00:29:17.714 --> 00:29:18.981
E.B.: So you don't want the job?

482
00:29:19.005 --> 00:29:21.422
- MASON: Did I say that?
- (E.B. LAUGHS)

483
00:29:21.506 --> 00:29:24.464
Bring me a signature
and a check.

484
00:29:27.964 --> 00:29:28.964
Cheer up.

485
00:29:29.005 --> 00:29:32.089
Someone might throw
a shoe at you.

486
00:29:32.172 --> 00:29:34.589
And you. get your hands
off my liquor and yourself

487
00:29:34.673 --> 00:29:36.673
down to the Angel's Flight
in the morning.

488
00:29:36.756 --> 00:29:38.547
Be my eyes. son.

489
00:29:39.089 --> 00:29:40.297
Time and a half.

490
00:29:40.381 --> 00:29:42.506
- It's New Year's Eve.
- Earn it.

491
00:29:48.673 --> 00:29:50.839
(LUPE PANTING)

492
00:29:52.381 --> 00:29:54.631
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

493
00:29:58.255 --> 00:30:02.422
- (MOANING)
- (BED SQUEAKING)

494
00:30:10.381 --> 00:30:13.589
(MOANING INTENSIFIES)

495
00:30:13.673 --> 00:30:15.172
- (LUPE YELPS)
- (OBJECT CLANGS)

496
00:30:20.381 --> 00:30:21.923
LUPE: Very good. papi.

497
00:30:23.339 --> 00:30:25.214
(COW MOOS)

498
00:30:26.673 --> 00:30:28.422
I think she's jealous of me.

